{"title_page": "Synod of Worms", "text_new": "[[File:Heinrich 4 g.jpg|thumb|Emperor Henry IV, from a gospel book of [[St. Emmeram's Abbey]] ({{circa|1106}})]]\nThe '''Synod of Worms''' was an ecclesiastical [[synod]] and Imperial diet (''[[Hoftag]]'') convened by the [[Kingdom of Germany|German]] king and emperor-elect [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry IV]] on 24 January 1076, at [[Worms, Germany|Worms]]. It was intended to agree a condemnation of [[Pope Gregory VII]], and Henry's success in achieving this outcome marked the beginning of the [[Investiture Controversy]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1067 Archbishop [[Guido da Velate|Guido of Milan]], facing the rising forces of the ''[[pataria]]'' reformers in the city, gave up his see. He recommended the subdeacon [[Gotofredo da Castiglione]] his successor, who, however, was excommunicated by [[Pope Alexander II]]. While Henry IV appointed Gotofredo in 1070, the patarines elected [[Atto (archbishop of Milan)|Atto]] archbishop. Three years later Pope Alexander II died and was succeeded by Hildebrand of Soana, who named himself Pope Gregory VII. An ardent proponent of the papal supremacy over Henry's emperorship, he promoted the [[Gregorian Reform]] as expressed in the ''[[Dictatus papae]]'' of March 1075, including the principle that the papal title is unique in the world and that it may even be permitted to him to depose emperors.\n\nNevertheless, when the ''pataria'' leader [[Erlembald]] died in April 1075, all signals pointed to reconciliation. Not until Henry IV again interfered in the Milan struggles and appointed Tebald da Castiglione archbishop, as well as bishops of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Spoleto-Norcia|Spoleto]] and [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Fermo|Fermo]], both on papal territory, the conflict escalated. In December 1075, Pope Gregory sent a harsh letter to Henry, threatening him with [[excommunication]].\n\nUnder pressure, the [[Salian dynasty|Salian]] king allied with the German episcopacy, benefitting from their hostile stance on the Gregorian Reform and a centralisation of church authority. Of the 38 German bishops, 24 attended.<ref>I. S. Robinson, ''The Papacy 1073-1198'' (1990) p. 402.</ref> Led by the ''[[primas Germaniae]]'', Archbishop [[Siegfried I (archbishop of Mainz)|Siegfried of Mainz]], Henry's supporters included Bishop [[Adalbero of W\u00fcrzburg]] and Bishop [[William I (Bishop of Utrecht)|William of Utrecht]], as well as the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge]] bishop [[Henri de Verdun]]. Cardinal [[Hugh of Remiremont]], who had already cut ties with the Pope, spoke damningly against Gregory.<ref>Robinson, p. 37.</ref> On the other hand, Archbishop [[Gebhard of Salzburg]], a supporter of Gregory like Bishop [[Altmann of Passau]], stayed away.\n\nThe assembly declared the Pope deposed and the bishops abandoned all obedience to him. Henry had a letter drawn up to Gregory, calling him 'Hildebrand the false monk' and demanding his resignation (''descende, descende!''). Three weeks later, the Pope declared Henry deposed and excommunicated him. He released all his subjects from their oath of allegiance, which soon became a serious threat for Henry's authority. In October, the German [[Princes of the Holy Roman Empire|princes]] gathered at [[Trebur]] and ultimately asked the king to reconcile with the Pope. In January 1077 Henry had to take the [[Road to Canossa]], to salvage his kingship.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Battle on the Elster]]\n* [[Concordat of Worms]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:1070s in the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:1076 in Europe]]\n[[Category:Imperial Diets (Holy Roman Empire)]]\n[[Category:Investiture Controversy]]\n[[Category:1070s in Germany]]\n[[Category:Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Heinrich 4 g.jpg|thumb|Emperor Henry IV, from a gospel book of [[St. Emmeram's Abbey]] ({{circa|1106}})]]\nThe '''Synod of Worms''' was an ecclesiastical [[synod]] and Imperial diet (''[[Hoftag]]'') convened by the [[Kingdom of Germany|German]] king and emperor-elect [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry IV]] on 24 January 1076, at [[Worms, Germany|Worms]]. It was intended to agree a condemnation of [[Pope Gregory VII]], and Henry's success in achieving this outcome marked the beginning of the [[Investiture Controversy]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1067 Archbishop [[Guido da Velate|Guido of Milan]], facing the rising forces of the ''[[pataria]]'' reformers in the city, gave up his see. He recommended the subdeacon [[Gotofredo da Castiglione]] his successor, who, however, was excommunicated by [[Pope Alexander II]]. While Henry IV appointed Gotofredo in 1070, the patarines elected [[Atto (archbishop of Milan)|Atto]] archbishop. Three years later Pope Alexander II died and was succeeded by Hildebrand of Soana, who named himself Pope Gregory VII. An ardent proponent of the papal supremacy over Henry's emperorship, he pushed the [[Gregorian Reform]] as expressed in the ''[[Dictatus papae]]'' of March 1075, including the principle that the papal title is unique in the world and that it may even be permitted to him to depose emperors.\n\nNevertheless, when the ''pataria'' leader [[Erlembald]] died in April 1075, all signals pointed to reconciliation. Not until Henry IV again interfered in the Milan struggles and appointed Tebald da Castiglione archbishop, as well as bishops of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Spoleto-Norcia|Spoleto]] and [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Fermo|Fermo]], both on papal territory, the conflict escalated. In December 1075, Pope Gregory sent a harsh letter to Henry, threatening him with [[excommunication]].\n\nUnder pressure, the [[Salian dynasty|Salian]] king allied with the German episcopacy, benefitting from their hostile stance on the Gregorian Reform and a centralisation of church authority. Of the 38 German bishops, 24 attended.<ref>I. S. Robinson, ''The Papacy 1073-1198'' (1990) p. 402.</ref> Led by the ''[[primas Germaniae]]'', Archbishop [[Siegfried I (archbishop of Mainz)|Siegfried of Mainz]], Henry's supporters included Bishop [[Adalbero of W\u00fcrzburg]] and Bishop [[William I (Bishop of Utrecht)|William of Utrecht]], as well as the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Li\u00e8ge|Li\u00e8ge]] bishop [[Henri de Verdun]]. Cardinal [[Hugh of Remiremont]], who had already cut ties with the Pope, spoke damningly against Gregory.<ref>Robinson, p. 37.</ref> On the other hand, Archbishop [[Gebhard of Salzburg]], a supporter of Gregory like Bishop [[Altmann of Passau]], stayed away.\n\nThe assembly declared the Pope deposed and the bishops abandoned all obedience to him. Henry had a letter drawn up to Gregory, calling him 'Hildebrand the false monk' and demanding his resignation (''descende, descende!''). Three weeks later, the Pope declared Henry deposed and excommunicated him. He released all his subjects from their oath of allegiance, which soon became a serious threat for Henry's authority. In October, the German [[Princes of the Holy Roman Empire|princes]] gathered at [[Trebur]] and ultimately asked the king to reconcile with the Pope. In January 1077 Henry had to take the [[Road to Canossa]], to salvage his kingship.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Battle on the Elster]]\n* [[Concordat of Worms]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:1070s in the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:1076 in Europe]]\n[[Category:Imperial Diets (Holy Roman Empire)]]\n[[Category:Investiture Controversy]]\n[[Category:1070s in Germany]]\n[[Category:Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor]]\n", "name_user": "Clivemacd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:use of language", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synod_of_Worms"}
